        <h3 data-uuid="3cd62768357e4615aa29d20804ba6d88">The Rise of McCarthy</h3>
        <p data-uuid="0eee7d817a1f440bbef69da65a436391">Wisconsin senator<dfn title="McCarthy, Joseph"> Joseph McCarthy</dfn> contributed
            to fears in the early 1950s by charging that Communists were working inside the
            State Department. He claimed to have the names of 57 people who were “either
            card-carrying members or certainly loyal to the Communist Party.”</p>
        <p data-uuid="db82b4e4959446eeb3b0f2b37f037081">
            McCarthy produced no
            concrete proof of crimes. Many people spoke out about McCarthy’s accusations in
            which he had no proof. When challenged, he made up new charges, labeling those
            who questioned him as “soft on communism.” This method of making aggressive
            accusations without proof became known as McCarthyism.</p>
        <section class="historical-source nobg" data-uuid="cc375dc3176045d08c8e06caa4173fe3">
            <article class="box gradient" data-uuid="81725df2fb294490a3cdfa09216ca5b4">
                <div class="header-element" data-uuid="b51e59f8f46346faa7afc8923f9f73a7">
                    <h2 class="label" data-uuid="0af5ca34bc0844e9b0c1cf9aaa45eb08"><b>Document-Based Investigation</b>   Historical Source</h2>
                </div>
                <div class="jonra" data-uuid="55ee4feb957540399c796b9a7c36b5bb">
                    <h2 data-uuid="4d84b448730a487c8320be8c5510101c">Exchange Between Edward R. Murrow and Joseph
                        McCarthy</h2>
                    <p class="source" data-uuid="cf3c47408f1c4672b23e8bdfcc768edc">Edward R. Murrow, a
                        prominent journalist of the time, frequently criticized Senator McCarthy’s
                        tactics. McCarthy’s response was furious&#160;and accusatory.</p>
                </div>
                <section class="compare-text " data-uuid="3eb54814a8df483d8b36e1ee79678c4c">
                    <figure class="green-star intro-star" data-uuid="56aca8b681c5450db2c2d003fa2a3b6b"></figure>
                    <article class="column-container intro-col" data-uuid="0082fc7bf2bf4e77af1854a1c0cf0c32">
                        <div data-uuid="85d83261cc34422fa7f4094fdfe86023">
                            <p class="red hang" data-uuid="3f0cb9104f6e4f0690051ec9b106dc12">“If none of us ever read
                                a book that was ‘dangerous,’ nor had a friend who was ‘different,’ or never
                                joined an organization that advocated ‘change,’ we would all be just the kind
                                of people Joe McCarthy wants. Whose fault is that? Not really [McCarthy’s]. He
                                didn’t create this situation of fear. He merely exploited [took advantage of]
                                it, and rather successfully.”</p>
                            <p class="source" data-uuid="896ddec931eb4ae78fb783ad616f4942">—Edward R. Murrow</p>
                        </div>
                        <div data-uuid="68b003d2da5c4f9c9046f07f0a4ce85e">
                            <p class="blue-2 hang" data-uuid="e092feb1ad12487790ead87a7d08cd72">“Murrow is a
                                symbol—the leader and the cleverest of the jackal [wild dog] pack which is always
                                found at the throat of anyone who dares to expose individual Communists and
                                traitors. I am compelled by the facts to say to you that Mr. Edward R. Murrow,
                                as far back as twenty years ago, was engaged in propaganda for Communist
                                causes.”&#160;</p>
                            <p class="source" data-uuid="ca121b791cef4d29b59c4dd84a94e43a">—Senator Joseph McCarthy</p>
                        </div>
                    </article>
                </section>
